<TITLE> Hearing halted on 5th amendment appeal </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Jan 11 (bdnews24.com)  The Supreme Court has postponed hearing for four weeks the appeal against the High Court ruling that stated that the fifth amendment to the constitution was illegal. The amendment had given legal cover to military rule and the laws formulated under such rule. A four-strong Appellate Division bench led by chief justice Ruhul Amin passd the order. On behalf of the government, the defendant, Zainul Abedin asked for time. The prosecution was represented by Azmalul Hossain, who was assisted by Siddiqur Rahman. "Following a time appeal from the government, the hearing has been suspended for four weeks by the appellate division," told Siddiqur told bdnews24.com. On Aug. 29, 2005, the High Court bench comprising justices ABM Khairul Huq and ATM Fazle Kabir declared the fifth amendment to the constitution was illegal. The court declared that the rule of Khandakar Mushtaque Ahmed, Abu Sada't Mohammad Sayem and Ziaur Rahman from Aug. 15, 1975 to 1979 was illegitimate. It, however, exonerated a series of works done by that specific government for public benefit. The judgement said military rule and the laws made under such rule were illegal. Changes in government from Aug. 15, 1975 until 1991 were not in accordance to the constitution, the HC ruling stated. The HC gave that verdict on a writ petition challenging the legitimacy of the Number 7 Martial Law Regulation (MLR) formulated in 1977. b
